[00:01.815]Passage 27. | 第27篇文章。
[00:03.285]Nothing to sell and nothing to buy. | 无物可售，无物可买。
[00:08.065]It has been said that everyone lives by selling something. | 有人曾说，人人都是靠出卖某种东西而生活的。
[00:12.795]In the light of this statement, teachers live by selling knowledge. | 根据这个说法，教师靠出卖知识而生活。
[00:17.385]Philosophers by selling wisdom, and priests by selling spiritual comfort. | 哲学家靠出卖智慧而生活，牧师靠出卖精神安慰而生活。
[00:22.995]Though it may be possible to measure the value of material goods in terms of money, | 虽然衡量物质商品的价值可以用金钱来衡量，
[00:27.535]it is extremely difficult to estimate the true value of the services which people perform for us. | 但要估计人们为我们提供的服务的真正价值却非常困难。
[000:34.425]There are times when we would willingly give everything we possess to save our lives. | 有时我们愿意付出我们所拥有的一切来挽救我们的生命。
[00:39.195]Yet we might grudge paying a surgeon a high fee for offering us precisely this service. | 然而，我们可能会不情愿地支付高额费用给外科医生，因为他为我们提供了这项服务。
[00:45.495]The conditions of society are such that skills have to be paid for in the same way that goods are paid for at a shop. | 社会的状况是这样的，技能必须像在商店里购买商品一样付费。
[00:53.645]Everyone has something to sell. | 每个人都有东西可以卖。
[00:56.885]Tramps seem to be the only exception to this general rule. | 流浪汉似乎是这条普遍规则的唯一例外。
[01:01.595]Beggars almost sell themselves as human beings to arouse the pity of passers-by. | 乞丐几乎是出卖自己作为人类的身份，以引起路人的怜悯。
[01:08.105]But real tramps are not beggars. | 但真正的流浪汉不是乞丐。
[01:11.145]They have nothing to sell and require nothing from others. | 他们没有什么可卖的，也不向别人索取什么。
[01:15.345]In seeking independence, they do not sacrifice their human dignity. | 在追求独立的过程中，他们不牺牲自己的人格尊严。
[01:20.405]A tramp may ask you for money, but he will never ask you to feel sorry for him. | 流浪汉可能会向你要钱，但他绝不会要求你同情他。
[01:26.135]He has deliberately chosen to lead the life he leads and is fully aware of the consequences. | 他是故意选择过这种生活的，并且完全清楚其后果。
[01:32.655]He may never be sure where the next meal is coming from. | 他可能永远不知道下一顿饭从哪里来。
[01:36.465]But he is free from the thousands of anxieties which afflict other people. | 但他却摆脱了困扰其他人的成千上万的焦虑。
[01:41.685]His few material possessions make it possible for him to move from place to place with ease. | 他少量的物质财产使他能够轻松地从一个地方移动到另一个地方。
[01:48.405]By having to sleep in the open, he gets far closer to the world of nature than most of us ever do. | 由于必须露宿野外，他比我们大多数人更接近大自然。
[01:55.445]He may hunt, beg, or steal occasionally to keep himself alive. | 他可能会偶尔打猎、乞讨或偷窃来维持生计。
[02:01.375]He may even, in times of real need, do a little work. | 在真正需要的时候，他甚至会做一点工作。
[02:05.575]But he will never sacrifice his freedom. | 但他绝不会牺牲自己的自由。
[02:09.305]We often speak with contempt for tramps and put them in the same class as beggars. | 我们常常轻蔑地谈论流浪汉，并将他们与乞丐归为一类。
[02:15.285]But how many of us can honestly say that we have not felt a little envious of their simple way of life and their freedom from care? | 但我们中有多少人能诚实地说，我们没有对他们简单的生活方式和无忧无虑感到一丝羡慕呢？